data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current code uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count check with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — reports *"expected 3 but got 5"* instead of just *"false"*
- **`CollectionAssert`** — use for richer collection checks:
  ```csharp
  CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));  // MSTest v3.8+
  CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);                       // reference check
  CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);                     // same items, any order
  ```
- **Add failure messages** to `Assert.IsTrue` when you must use it — otherwise failures are undiagnosable
- **`users.Any(...)` over `users.Single(...) != null`** — `Single` throws if not found, masking the real assertion

**Quick reference of useful collection assertions:**

| Goal | Use |
|---|---|
| Exact count | `Assert.AreEqual(3, list.Count)` |
| Not empty | `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` or `CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty` (v3.8+) |
| Contains item | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` |
| Same items, any order | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` |
| Same items, same order | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` |
| All match predicate | `Assert.IsTrue(list.All(predicate), "msg")` |
